SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a story, drama, or poem and explain how it is conveyed through details in the text; summarize the text.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which statement describes Steve's experience with the invention process?

M.Choice: Steve decides he will create an apple peeler and then helps his mom peel many apples.

P.Choice: Steve's teacher encourages him to do research before he begins to design his invention.

R.Choice: Steve notices it is difficult to peel apples, so he designs a machine to make the job go faster.

S.Choice: Steve's classmate tells him his invention is not original so Steve decides to try a different idea.

Content: Select TWO details from the passage that BEST support the correct answer to Part A.

A.Choice: “'Just what I needed — a volunteer,' Mom said, turning and handing him the peeler.” (paragraph 5)

B.Choice: “There has to be a better way of doing this, Steve thought as he scraped the blade against an apple.” (paragraph 6)

C.Choice: “'Inventions are often created as a result of trying to make a task easier,' Mrs. Nell had told the class.” (paragraph 7)

D.Choice: “'Hey,' said Jenny, ... as she examined each drawing. 'What's with the old- fashioned apple peeler?'” (paragraph 11)

E.Choice: “'Don't be discouraged,' Mrs. Nell surprised him by saying ... what matters is that you took the assignment seriously ...'” (paragraph 17)

SubTopics: Describe how a narrator's or speaker's point of view influences how events are described.
Content: How does the narrator's point of view affect what the reader knows about Steve's invention?

M.Choice: It allows the reader to understand that Steve is worried Mrs. Nell will think he copied the invention.

P.Choice: It informs the reader that Steve's invention can help his mom bake apple pies for bake sales.

R.Choice: It lets the reader know that Mrs. Nell is impressed with Steve's effort in tackling the assignment.

S.Choice: It warns the reader that Jenny's grandmother has an apple peeler much like the one Steve designs.

Be sure to use what you have learned about the setting, characters, and plot of the passage. Follow the conventions of standard written English.

:ibox:Manage your time carefully so that you can:

• plan your narrative and do some prewriting in the space provided in your test booklet.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a story, drama, or poem and explain how it is conveyed through details in the text; summarize the text.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which theme in passage 1 is similar to a theme in passage 2?

A.Choice: It is more important to be clever than to be sincere.

C.Choice: People cannot be told what to do.

Content: What is a major difference in the way the two stories develop that theme?

M.Choice: Passage 1 develops the theme by showing how jealousy can cause problems, while passage 2 develops the theme by showing that trickery rarely works.

P.Choice: Passage 1 develops the theme by relating the problems between people, while passage 2 develops the theme by showing that some people are easily fooled.

R.Choice: Passage 1 develops the theme by explaining how people react to bad news, while passage 2 develops the theme by showing people covering up bad feelings.

S.Choice: Passage 1 develops the theme by focusing on why people interact badly, while passage 2 develops the theme by showing how people get along.
